<p>I have a csv file with the following content:</p>  <pre><code>col1;col2;col3 1.0;10.0;100.0 2.0;20.0;200.0 3.0;30.0;300.0 </code></pre>  <p>Then I read it with pandas in the following way:</p>  <pre><code>df = pandas.read_csv('test.csv', sep=';', header=True) </code></pre>  <p>As a result I get the following data-frame:</p>  <pre><code>   1.0  10.0  100.0 0    2    20    200 1    3    30    300 </code></pre>  <p>It means that pandas used the <strong>second</strong> to give names to columns (the columns are named as 1.0, 10.0 and 100.0). If used <code>header = False</code> instead:</p>  <pre><code>df = pandas.read_csv('test.csv', sep=';', header=False) </code></pre>  <p>I get the following table:</p>  <pre><code>   col1  col2  col3 0     1    10   100 1     2    20   200 2     3    30   300 </code></pre>  <p>Which means that pandas used the first row as header in spite on the fact that I wrote explicitly that there is no header.</p>  <p>This behaviour is not intuitive to me. Can somebody explain what is happening?</p>